England’s Covid R number has dropped again and is now between 0.8 and 1.0, according to the latest government figures. Last week it was estimated to between 0.8 to 1.1. If R is greater than 1 the epidemic is generally seen to be growing; if R is less than 1 the epidemic is shrinking. Here’s what the R rate is in each region of England: East of England – 0.8 to 1.1 (down from 0.9 to 1.2) London – 0.8 to 1.0 (down from 0.9 to 1.2) Midlands – 0.8 to 1.0 (down from 0.8 to 1.1) North-east and Yorkshire –0.8 to 1.0 (up from 0.7 to 1.0) North-west – 0.8 to 1.0 (up from 0.7 to 1.0) South-east –0.8 to 1.0 (down from 0.9 to 1.2) South west –0.8 to 1.1 (down from 0.8 to 1.2)   The latest estimates are provided by the UK Health Security Agency.